{"author":{"id":"1949ffc23f11a8cb4f8c42a45c9ad241b49570df9a18687489e9ea78d87c54a3"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1772048175,"nonce":"rk7gJ4JnGAV0smeRIaCob9qhDdk=","title":"Adopt probe/metric nodes as loss targets","message":"[Imported from GitHub #44] (created 2026-01-27T03:35:45Z)\n\n## Summary\nMove loss targets from implicit \\\"where\\\" selectors to explicit probe/metric nodes in the graph, and bind loss terms to probe outputs.\n\n## Motivation\n- Eager models reduce the utility of implicit selectors; explicit probes are more inspectable and UI-friendly.\n- Loss configuration becomes a concrete graph wiring problem (better for validation, reuse, and visualization).\n- Probes can be reused by inspector/analysis views and training logs.\n\n## Proposal\n1. Add built-in **Probe/Metric** components that can tap node ports or state paths.\n2. Loss terms reference probe outputs by ID (not arbitrary state paths).\n3. UI: loss editor shows a term tree and lets users pick/drag probe outputs as targets.\n\n## Benefits\n- Clear, visual source of each loss term target.\n- Consistent with graph-first mental model.\n- Allows rich debugging (probe outputs can be plotted or inspected live).\n\n## Related opportunities (similar changes elsewhere)\n- Use probe nodes for **validation** (e.g., unbound outputs, type mismatches) and **analysis** (plots).\n- Reuse probes for **logging/metrics** in training runs.\n- Export pipeline: probes can map to report specs and figure configs.\n\n## Open questions\n- Do probes use a strict port schema or allow arbitrary state-path selection?\n- Should probe outputs be part of model execution, or a side-channel for logging only?\n\n---\n\n## Co-authorship\nCo-Authored-By: Codex (GPT-5) \u003ccodex@openai.com\u003e","files":null}]}